than their predecessors, rendering them deeply compatible with the ambitions of a state embroiling itself in a perpetual and unwinnable war.Surveying the cultural landscape of this sprawling conflict, Figuring Violence reveals the varied mechanisms by which these affects have been militarized. Rebecca Adelman tracks their convergences around six types of beings: civilian children, military children, military spouses, veterans with PTSD and TBI, Guantánamo detainees, and military dogs. All of these groups have become preferred objects of sentiment in wartime public culture, but they also have in common their status as political subjects who are partially or fully unknowable. They become visible to outsiders through a range of mediated and imaginative practices that are ostensibly motivated by concern or compassion. However, these practices actually function to reduce these beings to abstracted figures, silencing their political subjectivities and obscuring their suffering. As a result, they are erased and rendered hypervisible at once. Figuring Violence demonstrates that this dynamic ultimately propagates the very militarism that begets their victimization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aChildren of military personnelzUnited StatesxPsychology. 0aDeployment (Strategy)xPsychological aspects. 0aDogsxWar usezUnited States. 0aMilitarismzUnited StatesxPsychological aspects. 0aMilitary spouseszUnited StatesxPsychology. 0aPrisoners of warzUnited StatesxPsychology. 0aPsychology, Military. 0aVeteransxHealth and hygienezUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aAmerican militarism.  aPTSD and TBI.  aWar on Terror.  aaffect.  adetainees.  aimagination.  amediation.  amilitary children.  amilitary spouses.  amilitary working dogs.08iTitle is part of eBook package: